son)}}\n| 1980\n| 46\n| ''[[I've Got Something to Say]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other charted songs==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of singles, with selected chart positions, showing other relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:21em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak<br />chart<br />positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot Country Songs|{{Small|US Country}}]]<br/><ref name=\"Country Songs\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Easy Come, Easy Go\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1964\n| 14\n| ''Bill Anderson Sings''\n| {{efn|Released as the B-side to \"Five Little Fingers\".<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In Case You Ever Change Your Mind\"\n| 38\n| ''Showcase''\n| {{efn|Released as the B-side to \"Three A.M.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson -- \"Three AM\"/\"In Case You Ever Change Your Mind\" |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bill-Anderson-Three-AM-In-Case-You-Ever-Change-Your-Mind/release/14463775 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Time Out\"<br />{{Small|(with Jan Howard)}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1965\n| 44\n| ''If It's All the Same to You''\n| {{efn|Released as the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] to the single \"I Know You're Married (But I Love You Still)\"<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Golden Guitar\"\n| 11\n| ''Bright Lights and Country Music''\n| {{efn|Released as the B-side to \"I Love You Drops\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson -- \"Golden Guitar\"/\"I Love You Drops\" |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bill-Anderson-Golden-Guitar-I-Love-You-Drops/release/8409498 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Papa\"\n| 1967\n| 64\n| ''I Can Do Nothing Alone''\n| {{efn|Released as the B-side to \"No One's Gonna Hurt You Anymore\".<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"20th Century Fox\"\n| 1983\n| 71\n| ''Southern Fried''\n| {{efn|Released as a double A-side single to \"Son of the South\".<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Music videos==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of music videos, showing year released and director\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:22em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Wonder If God Likes Country Music\"\n| 1991\n| Stan Moore\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Thanks to You\"\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Billy Brown, Lee Willard\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/bill-anderson/515535/thanks-to-you.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Bill Anderson : Thanks to You|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Old Army Hat\"\n| 2014\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/bill-anderson/1097248/old-army-hat.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Bill Anderson : Old Army Hat|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Waffle House Christmas\" {{Small|(featuring various artists)}}\n| 2018\n| Lee Willard\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=Watts |first1=Cindy |title=Video debut: Kid Rock joins country stars to celebrate 'Waffle House Christmas' |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/11/29/waffle-house-christmas-music-video-debut-bill-anderson-kid-rock/2143535002/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/488518-Bill-Anderson-2 Bill Anderson discography] at [[Discogs]]\n\n\n{{Bill Anderson}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Bill}}\n[[Category:Country music discographies]]\n[[Category:Discographies of American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]]\n| Image           = Bill Anderson-Opry.jpg\n| Caption         = Bill Anderson at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2006.\n| Studio          = 45\n| Live            = 3\n| Compilation     = 10\n| Music videos    = 4\n| Singles         = 80\n| Option          = 6\n| Option name     = Other charted songs\n}}\nThe [[discography]] of American [[country music|country]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]] contains 45 [[studio album]]s, three [[live album]]s, ten [[compilation album]]s, four [[music video]]s, 80 [[single (music)|singles]] and six other charted songs. First a successful songwriter, Anderson got his own recording contract with [[Decca Records]] in 1958. His first singles were successful, beginning with \"That's What It's Like to Be Lonesome\". He had his first top ten hit on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles|country songs]] chart with \"[[The Tip of My Fingers]]\" (1960).<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Bill Anderson: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bill-anderson-mn0000057923/biography |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> This was followed by the top ten hits \"Walk Out Backwards\" (1960) and \"Po Folks\" (1962). His first single to top the ''Billboard'' country chart was 1962's \"[[Mama Sang a Song]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> In 1963, Anderson released his most successful single, \"[[Still (Bill Anderson song)|Still]]\". The song topped the country songs chart in April 1963,<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Still\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CSI/song/577036 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>, reached number 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]]<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> and peaked at number three on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|adult contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Still\" chart history: Adult Contemporary |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/ASI/song/577036 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> A studio album of the [[Still (Bill Anderson album)|same name]] peaked at number 36 on the [[Billboard 200]], Anderson's only album to place on that chart.<ref name=\"Pop\">{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson Chart History: Billboard 200 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/TLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the remainder of the 1960s, Anderson had a series of top ten singles on the ''Billboard'' country songs chart. Among these songs were the number one singles \"8\u00d710\" (1963), \"[[I Get the Fever]]\" (1966), and \"[[My Life (Throw It Away If I Want To)]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Decca Records also issued several studio albums by Anderson in the 1960s. Among the highlights was ''[[I Love You Drops]]'' (1966), which topped the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums|country albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''I Love You Drops'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CLP/song/831773 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Another notable release was ''My Life/But You Know I Love You'', which peaked at number four on the same chart in September 1969.<ref>{{cite web |title=''My Life/But You Know I Love You'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CLP/song/832050 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Anderson would also collaborate with [[Jan Howard]] during this time. Their 1967 single \"[[For Loving You]]\" reached number one on the country songs chart.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Their corresponding [[For Loving You (album)|album]] peaked at number 6 in March 1973.<ref>{{cite web |title=''For Loving You'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CLP/song/831618 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Anderson continued having top ten hits into the 1970s. This included the number one hits \"[[World of Make Believe]]\" (1973) and \"[[Sometimes (Bill Anderson song)|Sometimes]]\" (1976). His 1978 single, \"[[I Can't Wait Any Longer]]\" was his final top ten hit as recording artist.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> \n\nAnderson continued recording with Decca (now [[MCA Records|MCA]]) into the 1980s. His final studio release with the label was ''Nashville Mirrors'' (1980).<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson -- ''Nashville Mirrors'' (1980, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bill-Anderson-Nashville-Mirrors/release/1555806 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> He also continued recording sporadically during the decade. This included the release of ''A Place in the Country'' on his own label in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson -- ''A Place in the Country'' (1986, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bill-Anderson-A-Place-In-The-Country/master/1673947 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Singles by Anderson were also being issued during the 1980s. His final chart appearance was a remake of \"[[The Deck of Cards]]\" in 1991. The single peaked at number 60 that February.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Deck of Cards\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CSA |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> In 1998, he released his first major-label studio album in many years entitled ''Fine Wine''.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> This led to Anderson releasing a series of studio albums for various labels over the next decade. His most recent studio release was ''Anderson'' (2018) on the TWI label.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson: Album Discography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bill-anderson-mn0000057923/discography |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected chart positions, showing other relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart<br />positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"Pop\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Top Country Albums|US<br />{{Small|Country}}]]<br /><ref name=\"Country Albums\">{{cite web |title=Bill Anderson: Country Albums |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bill-anderson/chart-history/CLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[RPM (magazine)|CAN<br />{{Small|Country}}]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Search results for \"Bill Anderson\" -- Country Albums/CDs |url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/list.aspx?OCRText=Bill+Anderson&ChartEn=Country+Albums%2fCDs& |website=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Still (Bill Anderson album)|Still]]''\n|\n* Released: June 1963\n* Label: [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: [[Gramophone record|LP]]\n| 36 || 10 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Bill Anderson Sings]]''\n|\n* Released: February 1964\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014 || 7 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Showcase (Bill Anderson album)|Showcase]]''\n|\n* Released: November 1964\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Bright Lights and Country Music]]''\n|\n* Released: November 1965\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014 || 6 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[I Love You Drops]]''\n|\n* Released: August 1966\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014 || 1 || \u201