'[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Andrew Adamson]]\n|-\n|48\n|2006\n|''[[Akeelah and the Bee]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Doug Atchison]]\n|-\n|49\n|2007\n|''[[Why Did I Get Married?]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Tyler Perry]]\n|-\n|50\n|2009\n|''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|Pete Docter\n|-\n|51\n|2009\n|''[[The Blind Side (film)|The Blind Side]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[John Lee Hancock]]\n|-\n|52\n|2010\n|''[[The King's Speech]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Tom Hooper]]\n|-\n|53\n|2010\n|''[[Tangled]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|{{ublist|[[Nathan Greno]]|[[Byron Howard]]}}\n|-\n|54\n|2011\n|''[[Soul Surfer (film)|Soul Surfer]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Sean McNamara (director)|Sean McNamara]]\n|-\n|55\n|2011\n|''[[Courageous (film)|Courageous]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Alex Kendrick]]\n|-\n|56\n|2011\n|''[[Dolphin Tale]]''{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Charles Martin Smith]]\n|-\n|57\n|2011\n|''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Tate Taylor]]\n|-\n|58\n|2012\n|''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Joss Whedon]]\n|-\n|59\n|2012\n|''[[Argo (2012 film)|Argo]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Ben Affleck]]\n|-\n|60\n|2013\n|''[[42 (film)|42]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Brian Helgeland]]\n|-\n|61\n|2013\n|''[[Instructions Not Included]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Eugenio Derbez]]\n|-\n|62\n|2013\n|''[[The Best Man Holiday]]''{{r|Geier}}\n|[[Malcolm D. Lee]]\n|-\n|63\n|2013\n|''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|{{ublist|[[Chris Buck]]|[[Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)|Jennifer Lee]]}}\n|-\n|64\n|2013\n|''[[Lone Survivor]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Peter Berg]]\n|-\n|65\n|2014\n|''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Ava DuVernay]]\n|-\n|66\n|2014\n|''[[American Sniper]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Clint Eastwood]]\n|-\n|67\n|2015\n|''[[War Room (film)|War Room]]''{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/we-are-your-friends-war-room-no-escape-box-office-1201508969/|title='At Room Finds More Followers on Sunday, But 'Compton' is Still King - Monday Box Office Finals|publisher=Deadline|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=April 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|Alex Kendrick\n|-\n|68\n|2015\n|''[[Woodlawn (film)|Woodlawn]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Erwin Brothers]]\n|-\n|69\n|2016\n|''[[Miracles from Heaven (film)|Miracles from Heaven]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Patricia Riggen]]\n|-\n|70\n|2016\n|''[[Queen of Katwe]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Mira Nair]]\n|-\n|71\n|2016\n|''[[Hidden Figures]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/817600462119702528 |title=''Hidden Figures'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 6, 2017 |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Theodore Melfi]]\n|-\n|72\n|2016\n|''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/820147992464424960 |title=''Patriots Day'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|Peter Berg\n|-\n|73\n|2017\n|''[[Girls Trip]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/888601240426250240 |title=''Girls Trip'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|Malcolm D. Lee\n|-\n|74\n|2017\n|''[[Wonder (film)|Wonder]]''{{r|Geier}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/931862772408901632 |title=''Wonder'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=November 18, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Stephen Chbosky]]\n|-\n|75\n|2017\n|''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/933700299734306819 |title=''Coco'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=November 23, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Lee Unkrich]]\n|-\n\n|76\n|2018\n|''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/964728141104128000 |title=''Black Panther'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=February 16, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Ryan Coogler]]\n|-\n|77\n|2018\n|''[[I Can Only Imagine (film)|I Can Only Imagine]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/974875300155744256 |title=''I Can Only Imagine'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|Erwin Brothers\n|-\n|78\n|2018\n|''[[Love, Simon]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/974874869476114434 |title=''Love, Simon'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Greg Berlanti]]\n|-\n|79\n|2018\n|''[[Incredibles 2]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1007852488978939904 |title=''Incredibles 2'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=June 15, 2018 |accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|Brad Bird\n|-\n|80\n|2018\n|''[[The Hate U Give (film)|The Hate U Give]]''{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1053504188691361792 |title=''The Hate U Give'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=October 19, 2018 |accessdate=October 20, 2018}}</ref>\n|George Tillman Jr.\n|-\n|81\n|2018\n|''[[Green Book (film)|Green Book]]''{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/ralph-breaks-the-internet-creed-ii-thanksgiving-box-office-1202505947/|title='Ralph' Breaking The B.O. With $18.5M Weds., Potential Record $95M Five-Day; 'Creed II' Pumping $11.6M Opening Day, $61M Five-Day|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 25, 2018|first=Anthony|last= D'Alessandro|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|[[Peter Farrelly]]\n|-\n|82\n|2018\n|''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1073821054101970944 |title=''Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=December 14, 2018 |accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro |title='Spider-Verse' Catching $36M, 'The Mule' Carrying Near $18M, 'Mortal Engines' Fails To Start With $7M+ |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/spider-man-into-the-spider-verse-mortal-engines-clint-eastwood-the-mule-weekend-box-office-1202520137/|date=December 15, 2018 |accessdate=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|{{ublist|[[Bob Persichetti]]|[[Peter Ramsey]]|[[Rodney Rothman]]}}\n|-\n|83\n|2019\n|''[[Unplanned]]''{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1112932006357217280 |title=''Unplanned'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=April 1, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-dumbo-flies-26m-previews-1198097|title=Weekend Box Office: 'Dumbo' Disappoints With $45M U.S. Debut|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Pamela McClintock|date=March 31, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|{{ubl|Chuck Konzelman|Cary Solomon}}\n|-\n|84\n|2019\n|''[[Avengers: Endgame]]''{{r|Geier}}{{r|carbone20190710}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1121984159524634628 |title=''Avengers: Endgame'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|{{ubl|[[Anthony Russo (director)|Anthony Russo]]|[[Joe Russo (director)|Joe Russo]]}}\n|-\n|85\n|2019\n|''[[The Peanut Butter Falcon]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/dora-and-the-lost-city-of-gold-hobbs-shaw-the-kitchen-box-office-weekend-1202665153/|title='Hobbs' Hauls $25M; 'Scary Stories' Frighten 'Dora'; 'Kitchen' Sinks Melissa McCarthy & Tiffany Haddish To Career B.O. Lows \u2013 Saturday AM Update|last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 11, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|{{ubl|Tyler Nilson|Michael Schwartz}}\n|-\n|86\n|2019\n|''[[Overcomer (film)|Overcomer]]''{{r|Geier}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1165129692917063680 |title=''Overcomer'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=April 23, 2019 |accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/ready-or-not-angel-has-fallen-good-boys-box-office-weekend-1202701545/|title='Angel Has Fallen' Still Ascending Close To 'London' With $20M; Tarantino's 'Hollywood' Beating 'Basterds' \u2013 Saturday AM B.O.|last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Alex Kendrick\n|-\n|87\n|2019\n|''[[Harriet (film)|Harriet]]''{{r|Geier}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1190660462150443009 |title=''Harriet'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=November 2, 2019 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |title='Terminator: Dark Fate' Loads Up $2.4M On Halloween Night |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/terminator-dark-fate-linda-hamilton-harriet-motherless-brooklyn-weekend-box-office-1202774477/ |website=Deadline |accessdate=November 1, 2019 |date=November 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|[[Kasi Lemmons]]\n|-\n|88\n|2019\n|''[[Ford v Ferrari]]''{{r|Geier}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1195592107676905472 |title=''Ford v Ferrari'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=November 15, 2019 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-weekend-box-office-1202787070/ |title= 'Ford v Ferrari' Cruising To $28M+, 'Charlie's Angels' Kicked Out Of Heaven With $10M+ Start |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 14, 2019 |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|[[James Mangold]]\n|-\n|89\n|2019\n|''[[Just Mercy]]''{{r|Geier}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1216063663380946944 |title=''Just Mercy'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 11, 2020 |accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rise-skywalker-unwraps-huge-35m-christmas-little-women-opens-1264949|title=Box Office: 'Star Wars: Rise of Skywalker' Unwraps Huge $32M on Christmas Day|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 25, 2019 |accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|[[Destin Daniel Cretton]]\n|}\n\nAs of 2019, only two directors have made the list three times: Rob Reiner (1987, 1989, 1992) and Alex Kendrick (2011, 2015, 2019).  The following directors have been on the list two times: Steven Spielberg (1982, 1993), James Cameron (1991, 1997), Robert Zemeckis (1994, 2004), Pete Docter (2001, 2009), Malcolm D. Lee (2013, 2017), Peter Berg (2013, 2016), Erwin Brothers (2015, 2018), Brad Bird (2004, 2018) & George Tillman Jr. (1997, 2018).\n\n===List of F films===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!No.\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n|-\n|1\n|1999\n|''[[Eye of the Beholder (film)|Eye of the Beholder]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Stephan Elliott]]\n|-\n|2\n|2000\n|''[[Dr. T & the Women|Dr. T and the Women]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Robert Altman]]\n|-\n|3\n|2000\n|''[[Lost Souls (2000 film)|Lost Souls]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Janusz Kami\u0144ski]]\n|-\n|4\n|2000\n|''[[Lucky Numbers]]''{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Clark}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Nora Ephron]]\n|-\n|5\n|2002\n|''[[Darkness (2002 film)|Darkness]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Jaume Balaguer\u00f3]]\n|-\n|6\n|2002\n|''[[FeardotCom|Fear Dot Com]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[William Malone (director)|William Malone]]\n|-\n|7\n|2002\n|''[[Solaris (2002 film)|Solaris]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Steven Soderbergh]]\n|-\n|8\n|2003\n|''[[In the Cut]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Jane Campion]]\n|-\n|9\n|2005\n|''[[Alone in the Dark (2005 film)|Alone in the Dark]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Uwe Boll]]\n|-\n|10\n|2005\n|''[[Wolf Creek (film)|Wolf Creek]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Greg McLean]]\n|-\n|11\n|2006\n|''[[Bug (2006 film)|Bug]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[William Friedkin]]\n|-\n|12\n|2006\n|''[[The Wicker Man (2006 film)|The Wicker Man]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Neil LaBute]]\n|-\n|13\n|2007\n|''[[I Know Who Killed Me]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Chris Sivertson]]\n|-\n| 14\n| 2008\n| ''[[Disaster Movie]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Jason Friedberg]]<br>[[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Aaron Seltzer]]\n|-\n|15\n|2009\n|''[[The Box (2009 film)|The Box]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Richard Kelly (director)|Richard Kelly]]\n|-\n|16\n|2011\n|''[[Silent House (2011 film)|Silent House]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Chris Kentis]]<br>[[Laura Lau]]\n|-\n|17\n|2012\n|''[[Killing Them Softly]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[Andrew Dominik]]\n|-\n|18\n|2012\n|''[[The Devil Inside (film)|The Devil Inside]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}\n|[[William Brent Bell]]\n|-\n|19\n|2017\n|''[[Mother!]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|lincoln20170920}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/909035655493062656 |title=''Mother!'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=September 16, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Darren Aronofsky]]\n|-\n|20\n|2020\n|''[[The Grudge (2020 film)|The Grudge]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1213336695841513472 |title=''The Grudge'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 3, 2020 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Nicolas Pesce]]\n|-\n|21\n|2020\n|''[[The Turning (2020 film)|The Turning]]''{{r|Clark}}{{r|Geier&Fuster}}{{r|schedeen}}{{r|stopera}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/1220957297482051584 |title=''The Turning'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 25, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Floria Sigismondi]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n\n[[Category:Film organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Marketing research companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||music in film|film score}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name        = CinemaScore\n| logo        = Cinemascore-logo.svg\n| logo_size   = 260px\n| caption     = \n| type        = [[Private company]]\n| foundation  = {{start date and age|1979}}\n| founder     = Ed Mintz\n| location_city = [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| key_people  = \n| industry    = [[Marketing research]]\n| products    = Movies ratings\n| revenue     = \n| operating_income = \n| parent      = \n| homepage    = {{URL|https://www.cinemascore.com|cinemascore.com}}\n}}\n\n'''CinemaScore''' is a [[market research]] firm based in [[Las Vegas]]. It surveys film audiences to rate their viewing experiences with letter grades, reports the results, and forecasts [[box office]] receipts based on the data.\n\n==Background==\nEd Mintz founded CinemaScore in 1979 after disliking ''[[The Cheap Detective]]'' despite being a fan of [[Neil Simon]], and hearing another disappointed attendee wanting to hear the opinions of ordinary people instead of [[critic]]s. A [[Yom Kippur]] donation card with tabs inspired the survey cards given to audience members.<ref name=\"lawrence20160830\">{{Cite news |last=Lawrence |first=Christopher |date=2016-08-30 |title=Las Vegan's polling company keeps tabs on Hollywood |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/neon/las-vegan-s-polling-company-keeps-tabs-hollywood |department=Vegas Voices (story series) |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |access-date=March 19, 2017}}</ref> The company conducts surveys to audiences who have seen a film in theaters, asking them to rate the film and specifying what drew them to the film. Its results are published in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. CinemaScore also conducts surveys to determine audience interest in renting films on video, breaking the demographic down by age and sex and passing along information to video companies such as Fox Video Corporation.<ref name=springs>{{cite news | first=Chris | last=Wieland |date=March 20, 1993 | title=In Springs, Everybody's a Critic |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-03-20/features/9301310821_1_movie-untamed-heart-sommersby |newspaper=[[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]] |location=[[Broward County, Florida]] |accessdate=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCinemaScore pollster Dede Gilmore reported the trend in 1993, \"Most movies get easily a B-plus. I think people come wanting the entertainment. They have high expectations. They're more lenient with their grades. But as (moviegoers) do it more and more, they get to be stronger critics\". In 1993, films that were graded with an A included ''[[Scent of a Woman (1992 film)|Scent of a Woman]]'', ''[[A Few Good Men (film)|A Few Good Men]]'' and ''[[Falling Down]]''. Films graded with a B included ''[[Sommersby]]'' and ''[[Untamed Heart]]''. A C-grade film for the year was ''[[Body of Evidence (1993 film)|Body of Evidence]]''.<ref name=springs/>\n\nCinemaScore at first reported its findings to consumers, including a newspaper column and a radio show. After [[20th Century Fox]] approached the company in 1989, it began selling the data to studios instead.{{r|lawrence20160830}} A website was launched by CinemaScore in 1999,<ref name=\"Clark\">{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Travis |title=The 21 movies that audiences have hated the most in the past 2 decades |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/worst-movies-of-last-30-years-according-to-audiences-2017-9 |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=January 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> after three years' delay in which the president sought sponsorship from magazines and video companies. Brad Peppard was president of CinemaScore Online from 1999 to 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brad Peppard Salary Infomation 2012 |url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:https://www.erieri.com/executive/salary/brad-peppard-05xb+%22From+1999+to+2002,+Mr.+Peppard+was+President+of+CinemaScore+Online,+an+online+source+of+movie+rating+information%22 |publisher=ERI Economic Research Institute |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> The website included a database of nearly 2,000 feature films and the audiences' reactions to them. Prior to the launch, CinemaScore results had been published in ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' and ''[[Reno Gazette-Journal]]''. CinemaScore's expansion to the Internet included a weekly email subscription for [[Filmophile|cinephiles]] to keep up with reports of audience reactions.<ref name=expands>{{cite news | first=Carol | last=Cling | title=CinemaScore expands to Internet to offer moviegoers current information |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LVRB&p_theme=lvrb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=(+CinemaScore+expands+to+Internet+to+offer+moviegoers+current+information) |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal | publisher=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]] |date=September 16, 1999 |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, CinemaScore was rating approximately 140 films a year, including 98\u201399% of [[Major film studio|major studio]] releases. For each film, employees polled 400\u2013500 moviegoers in three of CinemaScore's 15 sites, which included the cities Las Vegas, [[Los Angeles]], [[San Diego]], [[Denver]], [[Milwaukee]], [[St. Louis]], [[Dallas]], [[Atlanta]], [[Tampa]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], and [[Coral Springs]].<ref name=expands/>\n\nIn the summer of 2002, CinemaScore reported that the season had the biggest collective grade since 1995. In the summer of 2000, 25 out of 32 films received either an [[Grade (education)#United States|A or B]] grade. Twenty-six of the summer of 2001's 30 films got similar grades, while 32 of the summer of 2002's 34 films got similar grades, the latter being the highest ratio in a decade.<ref>{{cite news | first=Scott | last=Bowles | title=Movies make the grade with fans, critics alike | work=[[USA Today]] | publisher=[[Gannett Company]] | date=2002-08-01 }}</ref>\n[[File:CinemaScore alt logo.svg|thumb|260px|Logo on movie ratings posted on [[Twitter]]]]\nSince July 2014, CinemaScore reports its results also on [[Twitter]],<ref>[https://twitter.com/CinemaScore CinemaScore's account] on [[Twitter]].</ref> and from January 16, 2016, it began with ''[[Collateral Beauty]]'' to use for each of them an image with the movie poster on the left and the grade obtained on the right.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/964728141104128000 |title=''Collateral Beauty'' |author=CinemaScore on Twitter |date=January 16, 2016 |accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2020}}\n\nUsually, only films that open in more than 1,500 screens are polled and reported on CinemaScore's website and social media. The distributor of a film that opens in fewer screens can optionally contract with CinemaScore for a private survey, whose result would be disclosed only to the client.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Alissa |date=August 13, 2018 |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2018/8/13/17657264/cinemascore-rotten-tomatoes-audience-score-metacritic-imdb |title=CinemaScore, Rotten Tomatoes, and movie audience scores, explained |publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rating==\n[[File:Cinemascore.jpg|thumb|right|A CinemaScore survey card]]\nCinemaScore describes itself as \"the industry leader in measuring movie appeal\".<ref name=\"aboutus\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cinemascore.com/aboutus |title=Cinemascore :: About Us |website=www.cinemascore.com |access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref> There are 35 to 45 teams of CinemaScore representatives present in 25 large cities across North America. Each Friday, representatives in five randomly chosen cities give opening-day audiences a small survey card.<ref name=\"mcclintock20110819\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-cinemascore-matters-box-office-225563 |title=Why CinemaScore Matters for Box Office |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 19, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2013 |author=McClintock, Pamela}}</ref>{{r|goldstein20091013}}{{r|busch20140809}} The card asks for age, gender, a grade for the film (A, B, C, D or F), whether they would rent or buy the film on DVD or Blu-ray, and why they chose the film.<ref name=\"goldstein20091013\">{{cite news |author=Goldstein, Patrick |url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/2009/oct/13/entertainment/et-bigpicture13 |title=CinemaScore's box-office swami |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 13, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref> CinemaScore typically receives about 400 cards per film;<ref name=\"cunningham20130618\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/cinemascore-gets-studios-especially-when-it-counters-critics-87701/ |title=CinemaScore Gets 'A' From Studios, Especially When It Counters Critics |work=[[TheWrap]] | date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=February 25, 2018 |author=Cunningham, Todd}}</ref> the company estimates a 65% [[response rate (survey)|response rate]] and 6% [[margin of error]].{{r|busch20140809}}\n\nAn overall grade of A+ and F is calculated as the average of the grades given by responders. In this case, grades other than F are qualified with a plus (high end), minus (low end) or neither (middle). The ratings are divided by gender and age groups (under 21, 21\u201334, 35 and up).<ref name=expands/> Film studios and other subscribers receive the data at about 11&nbsp;pm [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]]. CinemaScore publishes letter grades to the public on social media and, although the detailed data is proprietary, the grades become widely shared in the media and the industry. Subsequent advertisements for highly ranked films often cite their CinemaScore grades.{{r|goldstein20091013}}{{r|cunningham20130618}}{{r|busch20140809}}\n\nAs opening-night audiences are presumably more enthusiastic about a film than ordinary patrons, a C grade from them is \u2013 according to the ''Los Angeles Times'' \u2013 \"bad news, the equivalent of a failing grade\".<ref name=\"goldstein20091013\" /> According to Ed Mintz, \"A's generally are good, B's generally are shaky, and C's are terrible. D's and F's, they shouldn't have made the movie, or they promoted it funny and the absolute wrong crowd got into it\". Horror films consistently score lower; ''[[The Conjuring]]''{{'}}s A\u2212 was the first time a horror film scored better than B+. CinemaScore's Harold Mintz said that \"An F in a horror film is equivalent to a B\u2212 in a comedy\".{{r|lincoln20170920}}\n\nAn A+ grade from CinemaScore for a film typically predicts a successful box office. From 1982 to August 2011, only 52 films (about two a year) received the top grade, including seven [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] winners.{{r|mcclintock20110819}} From 2000 to January 2020, there were 53 movies with A+.<ref name=\"Geier\" >{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies-a-plus-cinemascore-lord-of-rings-harry-potter-black-panther-photos |title=53 Movies With A+ CinemaScore Since 2000, From 'Remember the Titans' to 'Just Mercy' (Photos) |work=TheWrap |date=January 12, 2020 |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |last=Geier |first=Thom}}</ref><ref name=\"carbone20190710\">{{cite web |last=Carbone |first=Gina |title=10 Recent Movies With An A+ CinemaScore That Are Worth Checking Out |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2476291/10-recent-movies-with-an-a-cinemascore-that-are-worth-checking-out |work=CinemaBlend |date=July 10, 2019 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> {{As of|2020|01|14|df=US}}, 89 films have received A+.\n\nFrom 2004 to 2014, those rated A+ and A had [[multiple (film)|multiple]]s of 4.8 and 3.6, respectively, while C-rated films' total revenue was 2.5 times their opening weekend.<ref name=\"busch20140809\">{{cite news | url=http://deadline.com/2014/08/b-grade-for-turtles-what-cinemascores-mean-and-why-exit-polling-matters-816538/ | title=B Grade For 'Turtles': What CinemaScores Mean And Why Exit Polling Matters | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 9, 2014 | accessdate=August 20, 2014 | author=Busch, Anita}}</ref> Ed Mintz cited [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Tom Cruise]] as the \"two stars, it doesn't matter how bad the film is, they can pull (the projections) up\".{{r|lawrence20160830}} (DiCaprio's ''[[Shutter Island (film)|Shutter Island]]'' had a 3.1 revenue multiple despite a C+ grade, and Cruise's ''[[Vanilla Sky]]'' had a 4 multiple with a D grade.){{r|busch20140809}}\n\n{{asof|2020}}, 21 films have received an F grade from CinemaScore.{{r|Clark}}<ref name=\"Geier&Fuster\">{{cite news |last=Geier |first=Thom |last2=Fuster |first2=Jeremy |title=All 21 Movies That Flunked CinemaScore With F Grade, From 'Solaris' to 'The Turning' (Photos) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/cinemascore-f-grade-movies-solaris-grudge/ |work=TheWrap |date=January 25, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"schedeen\">{{cite web |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |title=CinemaScore: 21 Movies Audiences Hated Most |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/cinemascore-13-movies-audiences-hated-most |website=[[IGN]] |date=January 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stopera\">{{cite web |last=Stopera |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Stopera |title=There Have Only Been 21 Movies That Have Ever Gotten \"F\" Ratings From CinemaScore \u2014 How Many Have You Seen? |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mjs538/movies-with-f-ratings |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] wrote that besides horror,<ref name=\"lincoln20170920\">{{cite news |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |title=What the 19 Movies to Ever Receive an 'F' CinemaScore Have in Common |url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/09/here-are-the-only-19-movies-to-ever-receive-an-f-cinemascore.html |work=[[vulture.com]] |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Another type of movie features prominently on the list: let's call it \"Misleading Auteurism.\" These are movies made by prominent, often Oscar-nominated directors that investigate risky and controversial subject matters and receive both praise and pans. But because of how the movie industry works \u2014 the name of a director alone not being enough to get most people to go see something \u2014 they tend to be marketed as more straight-ahead genre films, resulting in a whole bunch of misled and pissed-off audience members.}}\n\nVulture cited as examples of such F-graded films [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s ''[[Solaris (2002 film)|Solaris]]'' with [[George Clooney]], [[Andrew Dominik]]'s ''[[Killing Them Softly]]'' with [[Brad Pitt]], and [[Darren Aronofsky]]'s ''[[Mother!]]'' with [[Jennifer Lawrence]].{{r|lincoln20170920}}\n\nIn an essay for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', [[Martin Scorsese]] strongly criticized this type of approach by writing:<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scorsese |first=Martin |authorlink=Martin Scorsese |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/martin-scorsese-rotten-tomatoes-box-office-obsession-why-mother-was-misjudged-guest-column-1047286 |title=Martin Scorsese on Rotten Tomatoes, Box Office Obsession and Why 'Mother!' Was Misjudged (Guest Column) |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=October 10, 2017 |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The brutal judgmentalism that has made opening-weekend grosses into a bloodthirsty spectator sport seems to have encouraged an even more brutal approach to film reviewing. I'm talking about market research firms like CinemaScore [...]. They have everything to do with the movie business and absolutely nothing to do with either the creation or the intelligent viewing of film. The filmmaker is reduced to a content manufacturer and the viewer to an unadventurous consumer.}}\n\nCinemaScore's forecasts for box-office receipts based on the surveys are, according to the ''Los Angeles Times'', \"surprisingly accurate\" as \"most of [the company's] picks...are in the ballpark\", in 2009 correctly predicting the success of ''[[The Hangover (film)|The Hangover]]'' and the failure of ''[[Land of the Lost (film)|Land of the Lost]]''.<ref name=\"goldstein20091013\"/> Hollywood executives are divided on CinemaScore's accuracy. One told ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' \"It's not always right, but it's a pretty good indicator. I rely on it\", while another said that competitor [[PostTrak]] was \"much better...more thorough and in-depth\".{{r|busch20140809}}<ref>{{cite web |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |title=CinemaScore in Retreat as Studios Turn to PostTrak |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinemascore-retreat-as-studios-turn-648341 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===List of A+ films===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!No.\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n|-\n|1\n|1982\n|''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Steven Spielberg]]\n|-\n|2\n|1982\n|''[[Gandhi (film)|Gandhi]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Richard Attenborough]]\n|-\n|3\n|1982\n|''[[Rocky III]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Sylvester Stallone]]\n|-\n|4\n|1986\n|''[[Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Leonard Nimoy]]\n|-\n|5\n|1987\n|''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[Rob Reiner]]\n|-\n|6\n|1988\n|''[[Die Hard]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[John McTiernan]]\n|-\n|7\n|1989\n|''[[Dead Poets Society]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[Peter Weir]]\n|-\n|8\n|1989\n|''[[Driving Miss Daisy]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[Bruce Beresford]]\n|-\n|9\n|1989\n|''[[A Dry White Season]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[Euzhan Palcy]]\n|-\n|10\n|1989\n|''[[Lean on Me (film)|Lean on Me]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}\n|[[John G. Avildsen]]\n|-\n|11\n|1989\n|''[[Lethal Weapon 2]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Richard Donner]]\n|-\n|12\n|1989\n|''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|Rob Reiner\n|-\n|13\n|1990\n|''[[Dances with Wolves]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[Kevin Costner]]\n|-\n|14\n|1991\n|''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|{{ublist|[[Gary Trousdale]]|[[Kirk Wise]]}}\n|-\n|15\n|1991\n|''[[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]]''{{r|mcclintock20110819}}{{r|carbone20190710}}\n|[[James Cameron]]\n|-\n|16\n|199